Positive CAC scores can be classified as low (1-100), moderate (101-400), high (> 400), and very high (> 1,000) (
Table 1
).

sec.p:
T1 and T2 mapping can assist in the differential diagnosis of cardiomyopathies because these maps present different behaviors in each disease. T2 maps are very useful in identifying edema, while T1 maps have the ability to identify edema, diffuse fibrosis, and myocardial infiltration (
Table 24
).

Current evidence indicates that CMRA may be used in clinical practice to investigate the origin of coronary arteries and the presence of Kawasaki disease (proximal segments with larger diameters), with a Level of Evidence IIa (
Table 28
).

CMR in suspected myocarditis has a Class I indication for the diagnostic and prognostic investigation of acute and chronic myocarditis and/or suspected prior myocarditis (
Table 31
). The recent incorporation of parametric T1 and T2 mapping and ECV data increases diagnostic sensitivity.
